  "prompt": "What happens to a non capsulated bacteria?",
  "response": "When a non-capsulated bacteria lacks a capsule, several important consequences occur:\n\n1. Increased Vulnerability\n- Less protection against host immune system\n- More susceptible to phagocytosis by white blood cells\n- Higher likelihood of being destroyed by immune defenses\n\n2. Reduced Virulence\n- Decreased ability to evade host immune responses\n- Lower capacity to cause infections\n- Less resistance to environmental stressors\n\n3. Reduced Adherence\n- Lower ability to attach to host cells\n- Decreased potential for colonization\n- Less effective at establishing infection\n\n4. Altered Pathogenicity\n- Typically less invasive\n- Reduced capability to cause disease\n- More easily recognized and eliminated by immune system\n\n5. Potential Genetic Changes\n- May undergo mutations to compensate for capsule loss\n- Might develop alternative survival mechanisms\n\n6. Compromised Survival\n- More exposed to external environmental challenges\n- Greater risk of dehydration\n- Less protection against antibiotics and chemical agents\n\nThese consequences make non-capsulated bacteria generally less effective at causing infections compared to their capsulated counterparts.",
